{{For|persons with similar names|Jeannette Lee (disambiguation)}} {{Outdated|2=28 February 2008|date=August 2015}} {{Infobox sportsperson | name = | image = Jeanette Lee.JPG | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1971|07|09}} | birth_place = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | country = {{USA}} | nickname = Black Widow | medaltemplates = {{Medal|Sport | Women's [[nine-ball]] }} {{Medal|Country | the {{USA}} }} {{Medal|Competition | [[World Games]] }} {{Medal|Gold | [[World Games 2001|2001 Akita]] | [[Cue sports at the World Games 2001|Individual]] }} }}
'''Jeanette Lee''' (born Lee Jin-Hee, [[Hangul]]: 이진희, July 9, 1971 in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]]) is an American professional [[Pocket billiards|pool]] player. She was [[nickname]]d '''the Black Widow''' by her friends because, in spite of her sweet demeanor, she would "eat people alive" when she got to a pool table.<ref>[http://www.tv.com/american-chopper/the-jeanette-lee-black-widow-bike/episode/1311661/summary.html Reference to her nickname]</ref> Jeanette is an American of Korean descent.
==Career== Lee started playing pool in 1989. She went on to rank as the No. 1 female pool player in the world during the 1990s, and received the [[Women's Professional Billiard Association]] (WPBA) Sportsperson of the Year Award in 1998. She was three times runner-up at the World Nine-ball Championships ([[List of WPA World Nine-ball champions #Women's champions|women's]]), from 1993–96. In addition to many top finishes on the WPBA Tour, she won the [[gold medal]] for the United States at the 2001 [[World Games]] in [[Akita, Japan]], and won the ladies' {{US$}}25,000 winner-take-all Tournament of Champions twice, in 1999 and 2003. Lee also wrote ''The Black Widow's Guide to Killer Pool''.
In 2001, Lee challenged [[Efren Reyes]] to a {{Cuegloss|Race|race}}-to-13 [[exhibition match]] at [[nine-ball]], in [[Manila, Philippines]], but lost 4-13.
For<!--The use of "for" not "in" is intentional here; was not published until February 2008--> 2007, she was ranked #4 in ''Pool & Billiard Magazine''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s "Fans' Top 20 Favorite Players" poll.<ref name="PBM Feb. 2008 2">{{Cite magazine |title=The Survey Says...: ''Pool & Billiard Magazine''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s 22nd Annual Player and Fan Poll |magazine=Pool & Billiard Magazine |date=February 2008 |volume=26 |issue=2 |issn=1049-2852 |publisher=Sports Publications |location=[[Summerville, South Carolina]] |page=14 |accessdate=}}</ref>
